curves that do not allow a direct view of the planetary atmosphere as\nthey contain additional orbital processes. We discuss the implications of a\nbright-spot shift on the analysis of phase curves where both atmospheric and\ngravitational processes appear. We also discuss the potential detection of\nnon-transiting but otherwise similar planets, whose mass is too small to show a\ngravitational photometric signal but their atmospheric signal is detectable.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Apr 2015 09:59:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 7 Aug 2015 18:48:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-09-23"}
{"id":"1504.00499","submitter":"Martin Storath","authors":"Martin Storath, Andreas Weinmann, Michael Unser","title":"Exact algorithms for $L^1$-TV regularization of real-valued or\n  circle-valued signals","comments":null,"journal-ref":"SIAM Journal on Scientific Computing, 38(1):A614-A630, 2016","doi":"10.1137/15M101796X","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider $L^1$-TV regularization of univariate signals with values on the\nreal line or on the unit circle. While the real data space leads to a convex\noptimization problem, the problem is non-convex for circle-valued data. In this\npaper, we derive exact algorithms for both data spaces. A key ingredient is the\nreduction of the infinite search spaces to a finite set of configurations,\nwhich can be scanned by the Viterbi algorithm. To reduce the computational\ncomplexity of the involved tabulations, we extend the technique of distance\ntransforms to non-uniform grids and to the circular data space. In total, the\nproposed algorithms have complexity $\\mathscr{O}(KN)$ where $N$ is the length\nof the signal and $K$ is the number of different values in the data set. In\nparticular, the complexity is $\\mathscr{O}(N)$ for quantized data. It is the\nfirst exact algorithm for TV regularization with circle-valued data, and it is\ncompetitive with the state-of-the-art methods for scalar data, assuming that\nthe latter are quantized.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Apr 2015 10:02:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 13 May 2017 17:18:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-05-16"}
